post_text:
This year's summer reading program for our PreK-4 students is simple, silly, motivating and fun! Each time your child reads a book (or a chapter in a book for our older students), fill out this form. Have your child decide who they would like to "splash." Each time you vote for a particular Lincoln School staff member, we will add a cup of water to the bucket we will dump on top of them!

At the end of the summer, we will tally how many cups of water each staff member will get dumped on them. This program will run from June 15-August 15.

Short video explanation; https://drive.google.com/file/d/16gmcG4V1meGe-vo4VOPvZnyCVBpgrJyh/view?usp=sharing

Google form link;

https://forms.gle/uDFJRJE2ah1eUnAJ9

post_text:
Today the Blue Angels and Thunderbirds salute Coronavirus first repsonders. The first of the two flyovers, a 40-minute flight, will begin around 12:00 p.m. at the George Washington Bridge before the planes fly south along the Hudson River and over parts of Bergen, Hudson, Union and Essex counties. The flyover will then turn east toward New York City and continue above parts of Connecticut and Long Island, New York before concluding at 12:40 p.m. near the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge, which spans Staten Island and Brooklyn. Maybe you could take a peek outside at 12:00 p.m. While you may not be able to see them, you may be able to hear the jets.

I know many of our Rockaway parents and community members are on on the front lines each and every day so I would like to personally thank you for all you are doing to help us stay safe! #RockawayStrong

This morning we had two assemblies for our students (K&1 and 2&3). The presenters were Cassandra M. Faraci, Psy. D. and Connie Masullo, LCSW from the Center for Anxiety and Behavior Management. The students learned strategies for living mentally and emotionally healthy lives.

Thank you to the Rockaway Borough Municipal Alliance Committee for sponsoring these assemblies. We appreciate your support!

post_text: It’s so awesome when teachers work together! These beautiful Aboriginal art pieces were created with all the 2nd grade teachers and in Mrs. Isenberg’s Art class. Cross-curricular teaching, is an effective way to teach students transferable problem solving skills, give real-world meaning to school assignments, and increase engagement and rigor. At Lincoln we love working together!
